In .NET 10, Android's edge-to-edge mode is enabled by default, which means `adjustResize` alone no longer shrinks your layout. You need to respond to **keyboard (IME) insets** explicitly.

**Recommended approach — handle insets in your Android platform code:**

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Compatibility.Platform.Android;

public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        // Enable edge-to-edge insets handling
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
    }
}

class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View view, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var systemBar = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());

        // Apply bottom padding = max of keyboard or nav bar height
        int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, systemBar.Bottom);
        view.SetPadding(view.PaddingLeft, view.PaddingTop, view.PaddingRight, bottom);

        return insets;
    }
}
```

Also ensure your `AndroidManifest.xml` activity has:

```xml
android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize"
```

**Why this works:** Edge-to-edge draws behind the keyboard by default. The insets listener detects when the IME appears and adds bottom padding to push your input bar up.

**Tip:** If you want a smooth animated transition, replace the listener with `ViewCompat.SetWindowInsetsAnimationCallback` to animate the padding change frame-by-frame.
